- Ensure that you properly manage resource lifetimes. Since you're using raw pointers, be careful with resource deallocation to avoid memory leaks.
- Avoid directly returning or storing SDL pointers in your game engine’s public API to maintain abstraction over SDL.

Using a ResourceManager to centralize the loading and caching of surfaces is a good practice. It decouples resource loading from rendering and can make your code more modular and easier to maintain. Just make sure that your ResourceManager also handles the cleanup of the cached surfaces properly when they are no longer needed.

Sure! Creating a wrapper class around `SDL_Surface` is a good idea for keeping the SDL details hidden from the rest of your engine. A wrapper class can enhance the portability of your game engine and make it easier to extend or replace the underlying implementation in the future.

Here's a simple example of what such a Surface wrapper class might look like, accompanied with basic usage inside the ResourceManager:

```cpp
class Surface {
public:
    Surface(const std::string& filepath) : surface_(IMG_Load(filepath.c_str())) {
        if (surface_ == nullptr) {
            throw std::runtime_error("Failed to load image: " + filepath);
        }
    }

    ~Surface() {
        if (surface_ != nullptr) {
            SDL_FreeSurface(surface_);
        }
    }

    Surface(const Surface&) = delete; // Non-copyable
    Surface& operator=(const Surface&) = delete;

    Surface(Surface&& other) noexcept : surface_(other.surface_) {
        other.surface_ = nullptr;
    }

    Surface& operator=(Surface&& other) noexcept {
        if (this != &other) {
            if (surface_ != nullptr) {
                SDL_FreeSurface(surface_);
            }
            surface_ = other.surface_;
            other.surface_ = nullptr;
        }
        return *this;
    }

    SDL_Surface* GetSDL_Surface() const {
        return surface_;
    }

private:
    SDL_Surface* surface_;
};
```

In the ResourceManager, you would have a map holding your Surface objects. For example:

```cpp
class ResourceManager {
public:
    // ...

    Surface& GetSurface(const std::string& filepath) {
        auto it = surfaces.find(filepath);
        if (it == surfaces.end()) {
            // Construct a Surface and insert it into the map.
            auto result = surfaces.emplace(std::make_pair(filepath, Surface(filepath)));
            it = result.first;
        }
        return it->second;
    }

    // ...

private:
    std::map<std::string, Surface> surfaces; // A cache of surfaces keyed by file paths.
};
```

Then in the Renderer class, when you wish to convert a Surface to an SDL_Texture, you can use the `GetSDL_Surface()` method:

```cpp
class Renderer {
    // ...

    Texture LoadTexture(const std::string& filepath) {
        Surface& surface = ResourceManager::GetInstance().GetSurface(filepath);
        SDL_Surface* sdlSurface = surface.GetSDL_Surface();

        SDL_Texture* sdlTexture = SDL_CreateTextureFromSurface(renderer, sdlSurface);
        if (!sdlTexture) {
            // Handle texture creation failure
        }

        Texture texture;
        texture.sdlTexture = sdlTexture;
        // Set additional texture properties

        return texture;
    }

    // ...
};
```

Remember:
- Manage the SDL_Surface memory within the Surface class to ensure there are no leaks.
- Implement move semantics to eliminate unnecessary copying, especially since SDL_Surface ownership is now tied to the Surface object.
- Provide a method to get the underlying `SDL_Surface` for when you need to interface directly with SDL functions, but try to limit such usage to maintain abstraction.
- Since the ResourceManager now includes wrapper objects rather than raw `SDL_Surface` pointers, there's no need to call `SDL_FreeSurface` within the ResourceManager. The cleanup will be handled by their respective destructors.

By following this approach, your ResourceManager's `GetSurface` method will now return a reference to your Surface class, keeping the SDL implementation away from the user of your ResourceManager.

My ResourceManager now it giving me errors because previously I did the free surface in here, but now the new Surface is in charge of freeing the surface, how can I fix this?:

//class ResourceManager
std::unordered_map<std::string, Surface> surfaces;

ResourceManager::~ResourceManager()
{
    for (auto it = surfaces.begin(); it != surfaces.end(); ++it)
    {
        SDL_FreeSurface(it->second); //ERROR HERE
    }

