You're right—the error occurs because you're trying to free the internal SDL_Surface of the Surface wrapper using `SDL_FreeSurface` directly. After wrapping the `SDL_Surface` in your Surface class, the responsibility for managing the memory of the surface now resides entirely within the Surface class, specifically in its destructor.

Since Surface objects are now in charge of cleaning up their own SDL_Surface, you no longer need to (and should not) free the surfaces in the ResourceManager's destructor.

Just remove the freeing code from the ResourceManager's destructor, and leave the `surfaces.clear()` call to destroy all Surface objects, which will in turn call their destructors and free the SDL_Surface resources:

```cpp
// class ResourceManager
std::unordered_map<std::string, Surface> surfaces;

ResourceManager::~ResourceManager() {
    // No need to manually free the surfaces, as the Surface destructors will handle it.
    surfaces.clear(); // This will destroy all Surface instances.
}
```

As a side note, `surfaces.clear()` is not necessary in the destructor because the `unordered_map` will automatically clear its contents on destruction. However, including `clear()` in the destructor is not wrong and can sometimes be done for clarity or to ensure a specific order of operations during destruction.

In sum, since your Resource Manager is now using the Surface wrapper class, you can rely on the automatic memory management provided by the C++ destructor mechanism. When the Resource Manager is destroyed, it will destroy all contained Surface objects, and their destructors will take care of releasing the `SDL_Surface` resources. This is a great example of RAII (Resource Acquisition Is Initialization), a core concept in C++ resource management.

