The error you are encountering is due to trying to return a copy of Surface object by value, but you have explicitly deleted the copy constructor with `Surface(const Surface&) = delete;`. Since copying is not allowed for Surface objects, you need to return a reference or a pointer to the Surface object.

To fix the error, you should modify the return type of `ResourceManager::GetSurface` to return a reference to the Surface object. Here's how you can do that:

```cpp
Surface& ResourceManager::GetSurface(const std::string& filePath)
{
    auto it = surfaces.find(filePath);
    if (it == surfaces.end())
    {
        // Use emplace to construct the Surface object in-place
        auto result = surfaces.emplace(filePath, Surface(filePath));
        it = result.first;
    }

    return it->second;
}
```

By returning a reference (`Surface&`), you avoid invoking the copy constructor, and you still give access to the Surface object instance stored in the map. Since you are returning a reference to an object stored inside your `surfaces` map, you also ensure that the object's lifetime is managed by the `ResourceManager`.

Now when you call `GetSurface`, you will be working with the actual surface object managed by `ResourceManager`, and you won't be making any copies, which would otherwise be trying to invoke the deleted copy constructor.

One key thing to remember is that returning a reference means the caller must ensure they don't hold onto the reference after the ResourceManager or the underlying map could potentially destroy the object, which would usually be on ResourceManager's destruction. As long as the ResourceManager lives, and the filepath isn't removed from the map, the reference is safe to use.

My Surface code doesn't actually deal with failures, because as it works with pointers internally, the element will be NULL if it fails. What can I do about it?

Surface::Surface(const std::string& filePath)
{
    surface = IMG_Load(filePath.c_str());

    if (surface == NULL)
    {
        SDL_LogError(SDL_LOG_CATEGORY_ERROR, "ERROR: Surface '%s' could not be created: %s\n", filePath.c_str(), SDL_GetError());
    }
}

In your current `Surface` constructor, when `IMG_Load` fails, it logs an error message but does not prevent the rest of the code from continuing with a `NULL` `surface` pointer, which can lead to undefined behavior later on when the surface is used.

A common best practice to handle this kind of failure is to use exceptions. This way, if the `Surface` instantiation fails due to an inability to load the image, an exception can signal this exceptional condition to the calling code, giving it the opportunity to handle the error appropriately.

Here is an example modification of your `Surface` constructor to incorporate exception handling:

```cpp
#include <stdexcept> // For std::runtime_error

class Surface {
public:
    Surface(const std::string& filePath)
    {
        surface = IMG_Load(filePath.c_str());
        if (surface == nullptr)
        {
            std::string errorMsg = "ERROR: Surface '" + filePath +
                                   "' could not be created: " + SDL_GetError();
            SDL_LogError(SDL_LOG_CATEGORY_ERROR, "%s\n", errorMsg.c_str());
            throw std::runtime_error(errorMsg);
        }
    }

    // Rest of the implementation ...

private:
    SDL_Surface* surface;
};
```

With this modification, when a `Surface` object is created and `IMG_Load` fails, an `std::runtime_error` exception is thrown with an error message. This will immediately stop the construction process and propagate the error up the call stack, allowing it to be caught and handled where appropriate.

Now, when you use `GetSurface` from your `ResourceManager`, you'll need to consider the possibility of an exception being thrown, like this:

```cpp
Surface& ResourceManager::GetSurface(const std::string& filePath)
{
    auto it = surfaces.find(filePath);
    if (it == surfaces.end())
    {
        try {
            // Try to create the Surface; this may throw an exception.
            auto result = surfaces.emplace(filePath, Surface(filePath));
            it = result.first;
        } catch (const std::runtime_error& e) {
            // Handle the error, e.g., log it and/or take additional action.
            // Consider how you signal the caller of GetSurface about failure.
            SDL_LogError(SDL_LOG_CATEGORY_ERROR, "Failed to load surface: %s\n", e.what());
            // Alternatively, rethrow the exception or throw a new one.
            throw;
        }
    }

    return it->second;
}
```

By throwing and catching exceptions, you handle potential failures without passing `NULL` or invalid `surface` pointers around in your code. It enforces the idea that once `Surface` is constructed, it always represents a valid, loaded surface. Additionally, you preserve the guarantee to the caller that `GetSurface` either succeeds and returns a valid reference or throws an exception.

Remember, exception handling can add complexity and performance overhead if not used judiciously, so make sure it fits with the rest of your application's error-handling strategy. Ensure that any code that might throw exceptions is wrapped in a try-catch block where it makes sense, and that resources are handled correctly to avoid leaks (which can be assisted by using smart pointers or RAII containers).
